Dataset Information

Country: Name of the country

Region: continent of the country

Child_mort: child mortality under 5 years old per 1000 live births.

Health: total health spending per capita.

Exports: exports of goods per capita.

Imports: imports of goods per capita.

Income: net income per person.

Inflation: the measurement of the annual growth rate of the total GDP.

Life_expec: the average of years that a born child would live in a country with the same parameters.

Total_fer: the number of childr that would born to each woman.

Gdpp: GDP per capita.

Objective of this study

The aim of this study is to clarify which variables makes a new born vulnerable. Therefore, it increases the child mortality rate. My main hypothesis is that fertility rate and life expectancy are correlated with child mortality. And then, we have other economical factors that can contribute to increase child mortality such us exports, imports, inflation, income, GDP and Health, which can

Pre-process data and descriptive analysis

First, we have to download the csv country and region, and this last dataset we transform the column name into country to make a left join.

country <- read.csv("Country-data.csv")
region <- read.csv("all.csv")

region <- region |> 
  rename(country = name)

We do the left join and then, we use mutate, if_else to put the NAs of the regions that neither of the dataset datected.

result <- left_join(country, region, by = "country")

result <- result |> 
  mutate(region = if_else(country%in%c("Bolivia", "United States", "Venezuela", "St. Vincent and the Grenadines"), "Americas", region)) |> 
  mutate(region = if_else(country%in%c("Moldova", "Russia", "Slovak Republic", "United Kingdom", "Macedonia", "Czech Republic"), "Europe", region)) |> 
  mutate(region = if_else(country%in%c("Rep Dem Congo", " Rep Congo", "Cape Verde", "Cote d'Ivoire", "Tanzania"), "Africa", region)) |>  mutate(region = if_else(country%in%c("Vietnam", "South Korea", "Lao", "Iran", "Kyrgyz Republic", "Brunei"), "Asia", region)) |> 
  mutate(region = if_else(country%in%c("Micronesia. Fed. Sts."), "Oceania", region))

Finally, we check if we have only 5 regions.

x <- result |> 
  pull(region) |> 
  unique()

After this, we have a geom point to compare GDP and Fertility Rate. If we look carefully to the points, we see that a lower fertility rate is correlated with a high GDP. Most of the red points(Africa) have a high level of fertility and a low GDP.

We have similar result with life expectancy and total fertility. Hence, if a country has high GDP and Life expectancy, it will probably has a low fertility rate.

Feature engineering

For this part we will remove all the columns that do not have a numbers to use in the following techniques.

result_tidy <- result |> 
  select(-c(alpha.2,alpha.3,country.code,iso_3166.2,sub.region,intermediate.region,region.code,sub.region.code,intermediate.region.code))

In this matrix, we can see that child mortality, health, life expectancy and total fertility are a very correlated group. And the economical part, are quite correlated as well, and affects the health.

datos_numericos <- result_tidy |>  select(-country, -region)

cor_matrix <- cor(datos_numericos)

cor_df <- reshape2::melt(cor_matrix)



colors <- brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "RdYlBu")

ggplot(cor_df, aes(Var1, Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("%.2f", value)), color = "black", size = 3) +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = colors, limits = c(-1, 1), na.value = "white") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Matriz de correlación de variables") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

PCA

In this database, we do not have NAs, so we do not need to imput.

sapply(result_tidy, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
##    country child_mort    exports     health    imports     income  inflation 
##          0          0          0          0          0          0          0 
## life_expec  total_fer       gdpp     region 
##          0          0          0          0

With this code, we obtain the components of the PCA(Principal component analysis). The first component obtain the largest variation of the dataset, the second, the second largest and so on.

pca_result <- result_tidy |> 
  select(-c(country, region))

pca_result <- prcomp(pca_result,scale. = TRUE)
summary(pca_result)
## Importance of components:

When we plot it, with just 3 components we obtain more than 75% of variability.

fviz_screeplot(pca_result,addlabels = TRUE, barcolor = "white") +
  theme_classic()

Plotting it, we can visualiza that child mortality, life expectancy, total fertility, and income/gdp(those are quite similar) are the most importants components.

first_component_result <- pca_result$rotation[,1] |>  
  as.data.frame() |> 
  rename(weights = 1)

names <- rownames(first_component_result)
first_component_result <- cbind(names,first_component_result)

pca_plot <- first_component_result |> 
  ggplot()+
  aes(reorder(names,weights),weights)+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "white", fill = "blue")+
  theme_dark()+
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90),
        axis.title.x = element_blank())+
  labs(title = "First Principal Component")

pca_plot

Clusters

We remove the non-numerical columns.

cluster_result <- result_tidy |> 
  select(-c(country, region))

In order to make the cluster, we will select k = to 4

k <- 4
model <- kmeans(scale(cluster_result),centers = k,nstart = 100000)
centers <- model$centers

Now we make a barplot to figure it out how the clusters have been made. For example, the program has selected and group by countries with high mortality, fertility and low life expectancy.

barplot(centers[1,], las=2, col="darkblue")+
  theme_dark()

## NULL

Now we do the tidy data in order to understand the clusters.

means_ordered <- centers|> 
  as.data.frame() |> 
  mutate(cluster = row_number()) |> 
  pivot_longer(-cluster,names_to = "attribute")

And we plot them to see the information that each clusters contains and have been taken into account.

means_plot <- means_ordered |>  
  ggplot()+
  aes(as.factor(attribute),value, fill = as.factor(cluster))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
  #facet by cluster
  facet_wrap(~cluster)+
  theme_dark()+
  #rotate axis attributes
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90),
        #remove axis title to focus on the plot
        axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        #remove legend
        legend.position = "none")
means_plot

If we want to be more precise, we do silhouette and gap_stat to select the number of clusters. We will use gap_stat because the world is usually divided in 3 types of countries. Developed, under-developed and those that are in the middle.

fviz_nbclust(scale(cluster_result),kmeans,method = "silhouette",k.max = 10,nstart = 100)

fviz_nbclust(scale(cluster_result),kmeans,method = "gap_stat",k.max = 10,nstart = 100)

Hierarchical clustering

For this cluster dendrogram, we have divided it into 3 parts. Nevertheless, we cannot see clearly which are the countries within each of them. Probably blue and yellow part are those who perform better and worse.

d <- dist(scale(cluster_result),method = "euclidean")
hc <- hclust(d,method = "ward.D2")

fviz_dend(x = hc, 
          k=3,
          palette = "jco", 
          rect = TRUE, rect_fill = TRUE, cex=0.5,
          rect_border = "jco"          
)

Conclusions

To sum up, we can see how the child mortality divide the world in developed world(red), underdeveloped(green), and a blue part that are an intermediate group between both. The economy(GDP, Income) and the health(child mortality, fertility rate…) are quite correlated and allow us to analyse this phenomenon.
